\begin_layout Standard
Estimation of both abundance and demographic parameters are key parts of the management of wild populations.
 Obtaining these estimates with minimal bias and low uncertainty is critical for conservation.
 Mark-recapture (CITE) provides both estimates of abundance and demographic parameters simultaneously,
 at the cost of having to be able to identify individuals.
 Marks are can be natural (callosity patterns on the heads of right whales;
 CITE),
 artificial (bird ringing;
 CITE) or genetic (walrus crossbow shenanigans;
 CITE),
 but in all cases the method relies on the recapture of individuals to give information for estimation of survival,
 fecundity and abundance.
 Aside from changes in field methods,
 there is little difference in how models are constructed for these differing marks.
 Various models have been proposed over the last XXX years (CITE a bunch of Richard Cormack's papers?
 Or Ruth's textbook??),
 taking into account many common situations (e.g.,
 open vs.
 closed populations (CITE Richard Barker,
 Matt thingy from Otago etc).
 We can decompose our model parameters so that they depend on time,
 space and other environmental covariates (CITE Otis et al).
 Part of mark-recapture's success is surely down to its adaptability to new technologies for marking:
 from rings/bands to DNA.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If we use genetic marks to identify individuals,
 it seems that we are throwing away some of the extra information that exists in these samples.
 The DNA extracted from an individual will tell us about its relatives as well as the individual itself.
 Close-kin mark-recapture (CKMR) was developed to exploit the additional information which we obtain when taking genetic samples.
 So,
 as well as confirming that an individual as been 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

recaptured
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 we can also assess the probability that an individual has a given kin relationship with another (e.g.,
 making statements like 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

individual A is the mother of individual B with probability 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

).
 CKMR also has the advantage that both non-lethal and lethal (from sampling,
 hunting,
 natural mortality etc) samples can be used to gain kin information.
 By harnessing this extra information and putting kinship into a probabilistic framework,
 we can gain more accurate estimates of demographic parameters and abundance.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The kinds of kin relationships that can be inferred from DNA samples has increased over time,
 with advances in sequencing technology.
 Parent-offspring pairs provide the most basic level of information (though in some cases we may only be interested in one parent,
 as in the case study we present here,
 where mother-offspring pairs are of interest),
 but we can go further than that.
 We might also want to find full sibling pairs or half-sibling pairs too.
 Going back to parent-offspring pairs,
 how do we know which individual is the offspring and which is the parent?
 If we know the age of the individuals with complete accuracy then this problem is solved (the older one has to be the parent).
 We can't always determine the exact age,
 but may be able to get it to a reasonable range (or at least life stage).
 With the addition of age information we can include further kin relationships:
 even though genetically grandparent-grandchild pairs are not distinguishable from thiatic (niece/nephew-uncle/aunt) relationship,
 with age information (and some information about the life history of the organism) we can include these relationships in our analysis.
 It's also worth noting that despite the fact we never sample an individual,
 we still use information about them to estimate our parameters:
 e.g.,
 we might never sample a father,
 but if we sample his children they will show-up as half-siblings and so we will know about him.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The non-monetary cost of doing CKMR is that we must understand the life cycle and genetics of the organism in question in some depth.
 For example,
 CKMR will not work on species that reproduce via parthenogenesis (as offspring are genetically identical to parents,
 such as aphids) or species that give birth to clones (armadillos).
 CKMR would also be fairly ineffective for species that observe monogamous relationships,
 as the information from each additional capture is minimal.
 Knowing about reproductive strategy is obviously very important not just for sampling logistics:
 does the animal in question breed in one place?
 Does it observe a hareem structure?
 Does it do whatever fish do?
 etc 
