\begin_layout Standard
The monetary cost of doing CKMR is dropping in terms of sequencing,
 as new technology comes online.
 The non-lab costs remain as they ever were for mark-recapture (or any other observational study):
 person-hours in the field.
 As is the case with all field work,
 we want to get the maximum information for the minimum cost whilst also keeping people safe.
 So,
 we face the question every statistician dreads:
 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

how many samples do I need?
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 Fortunately,
 in the case of CKMR this is relatively easy to calculate,
 and that is the subject of this paper.
 Given a target coefficient of variation and information on demographics and abundance (from existing genetic surveys,
 pilot studies,
 or the literature),
 we can calculate how many kin pairs one is likely to obtain from a given number of samples.
 In this paper we show how to perform these calculations (and the information needed to do so) using a case study on walrus in the North Pacific.
\end_layout

